         <div type="translation" resp="part:reda part:emfr">
         	     
         	<p n="1">
		9th year of the king Parakesarivarman.          	</p>
         	
         	<p n="2-10">
		We, the great people of the assembly <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>peruṅkuṟi perumakkaḷōm</foreign></supplied> of the Śrī-Kāmaravalli-caturvetimaṅkalam, a <foreign>brahmadeya</foreign> on the north <supplied reason="subaudible">of the river</supplied>. After having the drum beaten <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>taṭṭaḻi koṭṭi</foreign></supplied> on the auspicious day of Kārttikai—which this year happened on a Thursday of the Dhanu month—the assembly, for the merit <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>cāṟṟi</foreign></supplied> of the assembly, gathered together in the <foreign>maṇḍapa</foreign> where we have granted an allowance <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>jivitam</foreign></supplied> for the maintenance of the holy offering <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>śrīpali</foreign></supplied> and the ritual of waking up of the Lord <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tiruppaḷḷi eḻucci</foreign></supplied>—as long as the sun and the moon endure—for our god Tirunallūr Parameśvara, which has gracefully  taken abode, and it consists of <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>āvatu</foreign></supplied>:
         	</p>
         	
         	<p n="10-14">
         		
         		so as to obtain <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>koḷḷa-p peṟuvat’ āka</foreign></supplied> on every harvest <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pūttōṟum</foreign></supplied>:    		
         		
		<list>
			<item>a <foreign>patakku</foreign> of paddy and a <foreign>tūṇi</foreign> for each <foreign>mā</foreign> extending <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>virivu</foreign><!--@VVG--></supplied> to all land that grows <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>viḷaiyum</foreign></supplied> rice irrigated <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pūci</foreign></supplied> with water <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>nīr</foreign>?<!--@VVG--></supplied> below <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>kīḻ</foreign><note>That is, “out of”.</note></supplied> the holy <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>śrī</foreign></supplied> Kōtaṇṭarāma channel, <supplied reason="subaudible">and</supplied></item>
         	
			<item>a <foreign>kuṟuṇi</foreign> of paddy for each <foreign>mā</foreign> in case the paddy is attached to the embankment <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>aṇai<!--@VVG--></foreign></supplied>. </item></list>
         	</p>
         	
         	<p n="14-16">
			so that the village commitee from the great assembly authorises people <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>iṭakkaṭavar</foreign></supplied> to enter the garden <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tōppu</foreign></supplied> during new moon.  
			</p>
         	
         	<p n="17-18">
				the temple administrators <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tēvakaṉmikaḷ</foreign></supplied>, according to <gap reason="undefined"/>, appoint people to collect taxes <gap reason="undefined"/>
			</p>
         	
         	<p n="18-20">
				so that the <supplied reason="subaudible">service of</supplied> beating <supplied reason="subaudible">of the drums</supplied> <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>koṭṭuvataṟku</foreign></supplied> in <foreign>śrībali</foreign> happens, as long as the sun and the moon endure, taking this paddy in this way <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>ipparicu</foreign></supplied>:
         	
         	</p>
         	<p n="20-22">
         	through the order of Bhaṭṭaṉ Nakkanākaṉ from Nallūr in all the four directions, 
         	</p>
         	<p n="22-24">
         	 through the order of Nārayaṇaṉ Nārayaṇaṉ from Kaṭavūr 
         	</p>
         	<p n="24-25">
         	through the order of Tirukkuṟuṅkuṭi Kramavittaṉ from the royal mutt <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>kō-māṭam</foreign></supplied>
         	</p>	
         	<p n="25-27">
         	through the order of Pattipōḻ Nārāyaṇahaṭṭaṉ from Kirāñcikkam.
         		</p>
         		
         		<p n="27-29">
				We, the great people of the assembly, have had it engraved in stone it stays like this <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>niṟppatu</foreign></supplied> as long as the sun and the moon endure.		
         		</p>
         		
         		<p n="30-34">
         		Through the order <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>paṇiyāl</foreign></supplied> of the village officer <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>madhyastaṉ</foreign></supplied> Amaṇamaṅkalayaṉ,<hi rend="italic">alias</hi>... nūṟṟuvan from the three hundred <supplied reason="subaudible">officers</supplied>. This is my signature.
         		</p>
         		
			<p n="34-36">
         		Through the order <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>paṇiyāl</foreign></supplied> of the village officer <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>madhyastaṉ</foreign></supplied> Brahmapiriyaṉ. This is my signature.
         		</p>
         	
         	<p n="36-39">
         		Through the order <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>paṇiyāl</foreign></supplied> <supplied reason="subaudible">commanded by</supplied> me Pūtaṉ Śrīkaṇṭa, <foreign>alias</foreign> Peruṅkāviti from Marutūr.
   
         	</p>
         	
         	<p n="40-42">
         		Through the order <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>paṇiyāl</foreign></supplied> of 74 village officers <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>madhyastaṉ</foreign></supplied> <!--what is the 74 doing here?-->.          		
         	</p>
         	
         	<p n="42-44">
         		Through the order <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>paṇiyāl</foreign></supplied> of the village officer <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>madhyastaṉ</foreign></supplied> Tiruveḷḷarai Peruṅkāviti<gap reason="undefined"/>.   		
         	</p>
         	
         </div>

